comment.narrative:
Baseline 1:
1.1.	Uzbekistan is in compliance with 2015-2017 Montreal Protocol (MP) mandated HCFC reduction targets and implements MSP GEF programme to meet final milestones by 2020 and 2030 respectively

Baseline 2:
2.1.	No survey of ODS alternatives use in Uzbekistan previously conducted;
2.2.	No systematic data on ODS alternatives use in Uzbekistan to enable accurate decision-making;
2.3.	Current legislation, i.e. Law on Atmosphere Air Protection, is outdated (because a number of years passed from its adoption) and may hinder the completion of the accelerated HCFC phase-out;
2.4.	Central Customs Laboratory of the State Customs Committee has outdated refrigerant standards for calibrating their gas chromatographs to ensure accurate measurement of HCFC substances during import/export/transit operations which inhibits enforcement action on illegal trade; 
2.5.	Limited knowledge on the side of environmental inspectors and importers of HCFCs about the newly introduced national system of ODS/ODS alternatives import/export electronic declaration which limits the effective operation of the system;
2.6.	The limited capacity of the State Customs Committee on storage of seized smuggled ODS/ODS alternatives resulting in ineffective management of seized ODS;
2.7.	Participation in regional UN Environment supported CAP network meetings and conferences are constrained by limited in-house resources which impedes information exchange on modern HCFC control procedures.

Baseline 3:
3.1.	Current coverage of the HCFC re-use system is limited and requires an extension to the national level; limited basic servicing tools to strengthening HCFC re-use;
3.2.	Lack of special servicing equipment for zero-ODS and low GWP technologies to support the transition from HCFC-based technologies to non-HCFC based ones;
